ladders.explanation:
This level implements the core matching logic that processes string and pattern characters while handling '*' specially. The key insight is greedy matching: when we encounter '*', we don't immediately decide what it matches—we record its position and continue, effectively matching it against an empty sequence initially. We only extend this match when necessary via backtracking. The algorithm processes characters left to right with three cases: 1) Direct match (same characters or '?'), 2) '*' encounter (record position), 3) Mismatch with available '*' (backtrack). The greedy approach works because if a match exists, the earliest '*' that needs to match more characters will be discovered through backtracking. This avoids the exponential complexity of trying all possible '*' matches upfront.

Algorithm:
while s_ptr < len(s):
    if p_ptr < len(p) and (p[p_ptr] == '?' or p[p_ptr] == s[s_ptr]):
        s_ptr += 1; p_ptr += 1
    elif p_ptr < len(p) and p[p_ptr] == '*':
        star_idx = p_ptr; match_idx = s_ptr; p_ptr += 1
    elif star_idx != -1:
        p_ptr = star_idx + 1; match_idx += 1; s_ptr = match_idx
    else:
        return False

Time: O(n+m) worst case. Space: O(1). This connects to L1 by providing the context where backtracking is invoked.

Common mistakes: Not advancing p_ptr after '*', incorrect condition ordering. Avoid by processing cases in the order shown.

Real code pattern:
def match_core(s, p):
    s_ptr, p_ptr = 0, 0
    star_idx, match_idx = -1, -1
    while s_ptr < len(s):
        if p_ptr < len(p) and (p[p_ptr] == '?' or p[p_ptr] == s[s_ptr]):
            s_ptr += 1
            p_ptr += 1
        elif p_ptr < len(p) and p[p_ptr] == '*':
            star_idx = p_ptr
            match_idx = s_ptr
            p_ptr += 1
        elif star_idx != -1:
            p_ptr = star_idx + 1
            match_idx += 1
            s_ptr = match_idx
        else:
            return False
    return True

This fundamental operation involves moving pointers (indices) through strings while checking bounds. In the wildcard matching algorithm, we have two pointers: s_ptr for the string and p_ptr for the pattern. We need to advance these pointers safely—only when we're within the string/pattern length. The intuition is that we can only access characters at valid indices, and we need to know when we've reached the end of either sequence. This operation is basic but critical: incorrect pointer handling leads to index errors or incorrect results.

Algorithm:
1. To advance s_ptr: if s_ptr < len(s): s_ptr += 1
2. To advance p_ptr: if p_ptr < len(p): p_ptr += 1
3. To check if at end: s_ptr == len(s) or p_ptr == len(p)

In practice, we often advance both pointers together when characters match, or advance them separately in different cases. Time: O(1). Space: O(1). This connects to L3 by providing the mechanism to move through strings during character matching.

Common mistakes: Advancing beyond array bounds, not checking bounds before access, confusing 0-based indexing. Avoid by always using < len() for bounds checks.

Real code pattern:
def advance_safe(s, s_ptr, p, p_ptr, advance_both=False):
    if advance_both:
        if s_ptr < len(s) and p_ptr < len(p):
            return s_ptr + 1, p_ptr + 1
    else:
        if s_ptr < len(s):
            return s_ptr + 1, p_ptr
        if p_ptr < len(p):
            return s_ptr, p_ptr + 1
    return s_ptr, p_ptr
